## Sources Investigated
I evaluated three PSA sources this week. All are publicly accessible without registration or a data request form.

### Source 1 — PSA OpenSTAT: Full Year Poverty Statistics
**URL:** https://openstat.psa.gov.ph/PXWeb/pxweb/en/DB/DB__1E__FY/?tablelist=true

This is the PSA's PX-Web statistical portal. I navigated to the Full Year Poverty Statistics database and confirmed the following tables are present and exportable:
| Table No. | Title | Format | Years Available |
|---|---|---|---|
| Table 1 | Poverty Incidence Among Families + Per Capita Poverty Threshold, by Region and Province | CSV / XLSX | 2015, 2018, 2021, 2023 |
| Table 1a | Same as Table 1, extended to Highly Urbanized Cities (HUCs) | CSV / XLSX | 2018, 2021, 2023 |
| Table 2 | Poverty Incidence Among Population, by Region and Province | CSV / XLSX | 2015, 2018, 2021, 2023 |
| Table 5 | Magnitude of Poor Families ('000), by Region and Province | CSV / XLSX | 2015, 2018, 2021 |
| Table 6 | Magnitude of Poor Population ('000), by Region and Province | CSV / XLSX | 2015, 2018, 2021 |
| Table 10 | Income Gap with Measures of Precision, by Region and Province | CSV / XLSX | 2018, 2021, 2023 |
| Table 11 | Poverty Gap with Measures of Precision, by Region and Province | CSV / XLSX | 2018, 2021, 2023 |

**File format:** Each table is exported as a flat CSV or XLSX file directly from the portal with no login required. Rows represent geographic units (national → region → province). Columns represent the metric values, coefficients of variation, standard errors, and confidence intervals for each survey year.

**Granularity:** National → Regional → Provincial → HUC (city level). The regional and provincial levels are what this project needs. HUC-level data is available from 2018 onward only.

**Update frequency:** Every three years, aligned with the FIES survey cycle. Last updated September 2024 with 2023 data. Next expected update: 2027 (2026 FIES cycle).

**Coverage check against the problem statement:**

| Project KPI | Available in this source? | Table |
|---|---|---|
| Poverty incidence (%) among families, by region | ✅ Yes | Table 1 |
| Poverty incidence (%) among population, by region | ✅ Yes | Table 2 |
| Annual per capita poverty threshold (PhP), by region | ✅ Yes | Table 1 |
| Income gap (%), by region | ✅ Yes | Table 10 |
| Poverty gap (%), by region | ✅ Yes | Table 11 |
| Magnitude of poor families ('000), by region | ✅ Yes | Table 5 |
| Point-change in poverty incidence across years | ✅ Computable from Tables 1 & 2 | — |
| Caraga province-level breakdown | ✅ Yes — all five provinces present | Table 1 |

Every KPI defined in M0 is either directly published in this source or computable from it. No proxy variables or external datasets are needed.

**Known gaps and limitations:**
- The 2015 tables use a 2006-based CPI, while 2018 onward use a 2012-based CPI. Poverty **thresholds in peso terms** are not directly comparable across cycles. Poverty **incidence rates and income gap percentages** remain comparable because they are relative measures.
- Provincial estimates for very small provinces carry coefficients of variation above 20%, flagged by PSA as unreliable for ranking. Cluster groupings (poorest, least poor) are used instead of point rankings.
- BARMM and Sulu 2021 figures were revised post-release due to food price corrections. The portal shows the corrected figures; older cached downloads from early 2022 may not.
- Table 5 and Table 6 (magnitude of poor) currently show data up to 2021 only. The 2023 magnitude figures are reported in the official PDF publication but have not yet been added to the OpenSTAT portal tables as of the time of this writing.
- HUC-level data (Table 1a) starts from 2018 — Butuan City's poverty trend, for example, can only be tracked from 2018 forward, not from 2015.

