## Refresh Architecture
The dashboard will run on a **semi-automated refresh model** matched to the PSA's three-year FIES cycle. When new data is released (next expected: 2026/2027):

| Step | Action | Who | Time |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | PSA publishes new FIES cycle data on OpenSTAT | PSA | Every ~3 years |
| 2 | Download updated CSV exports from OpenSTAT | Developer | ~30 min |
| 3 | Replace source CSVs in the project `/data` folder | Developer | ~5 min |
| 4 | Dashboard reads new files on next load; all charts update | Automatic | 0 min |
| 5 | Check outputs for methodology changes or data anomalies | Developer | ~1–2 hours |

**Design principles that make this work:**
- No hardcoded survey years — the year column is a dynamic axis, so 2026 data appears as a new point automatically.
- No hardcoded region list — regions are read from the data, so structural changes (like NIR or BARMM) are reflected automatically.
- Canonical column schema enforced by a cleaning script — any new OpenSTAT export maps to the same column names regardless of minor formatting changes.

**Known refresh risks:**
- PSA may change CPI base years or regional compositions again in the 2026 cycle, requiring manual recalibration of historical comparisons.
- Table 5 and Table 6 (magnitude) may lag behind other tables in being updated on OpenSTAT, as seen with the 2023 cycle.
- Full provincial data for the new cycle may not be available until 12–18 months after the survey year closes.

**Stretch goal (post-Week 16):** Replace the manual CSV download step with a direct query to the PSA OpenSTAT PX-Web JSON API, making the refresh fully programmatic.

